title: Grateful Dead Live at Henry J. Kaiser Convention Center on 1985-02-19
description: Jack Straw, Dupree's Diamond Blues, Minglewood Blues, Brown Eyed Women, My Brother Esau, Bird Song, Hell In A Bucket-> Might As Well Truckin'-> Terrapin Station-> Women Are Smarter-> Drums-> Throwing Stones-> Touch Of Gray, E: Johnny B. Goode

reviews.review_text: Not Their Best Good recording, but the band is not at their best.
80s dead not a big fan of 80s dead sound quality isnt bad tho

Historic, Though Maybe not one of their best performances, but the Women>Aiko>Women is certainly historic.  I've been wondering for twenty years why they never did a medley of these two songs -- which are musically virtually identical.  Well, they did, and here it is!  So at least grab these three tracks and check 'em out.

yea the 80,s Yea I really like the Grateful 80's.I think the 80s were some of there best years.Yea ther were some bad shows and bad Recording's but with the soundboards out know there are so many great shows to here.There were some really good shows in the 90's but but they were rare,When they were on they were really on in the 90's and then there were good shows in the 70's the only thing is some of there best songs were not out yet,But the ones that were out are some of the deads finest and the root of them and.They still were a great band back then.!The other thing is I did not like donna and I thought she just killed some of the best shows in the 70's.But I think Brent was the best Keyboardist they had,he was great so I have to say the 80's were the best and 89 was there best yearI think.This show does not do the band good bad recording kinda and they were a little off.I have to give it a 2.The night before was a good show I thought.

Not one of their best. This is a very short, unenthusiastic show with very few highlights.  The show starts off nicely with a decent Jack Straw that has good energy with some vocal flubs.  Dupree's follows and while always a nice surprise, Jerry's voice is croaking and cracking all over the place.  He kind of sounds like he's dying.  Musically well performed however.  Minglewood is a disaster with lots of mistakes and uninspired playing.  Jerry's vocals improve a bit for Brown Eyed Women but he makes lots of lyric flubs.  Esau is one of the highlights of the set with strong vocals and instrumentation.  Bird Song has some troubles in the beginning, especially craggy vocals and lyric flubs.  The jam however takes off nicely and turns this into a serviceable rendition.  The Bucket>Might As Well set-ender is very sloppy and lacks energy.

The second set is a bit of an improvement but it is terribly short with very little jamming.  Truckin' is strong but the post vocal jam is cu short, segueing into a decent Terrapin.  Jerry's vocals are a bit rough but it's a pretty good rendition.  Woman Smarter is the highlight of the set.  It is long and Bobby sings a bit of Iko in the middle.  The post Space jam consists of only two songs, a subpar Throwing Stones and a godawful Touch with brutal vocals and lyric flubs aplenty.  This show is a huge let down.

Not So Good I sadly remember this show all too well.  While it's not in Boreal territory, it's mighty close.  Even with a very cool Bird Song > Bucket > Might As Well closer for the first set, it's still meh.  I was ready to write the band off after this night.  Fortunately the Greek shows in June turned me around.

WCSTW-One More Time They have a snap to their sound in 1985- kinda like STATIC ELECTRICITY. ---Not sure when it was but when the band purchased those huge glass round clear electric charged globes that they had up on stage--- I thought man that perfectly captures what the Dead are all about. The electric current would change colors and patterns based on what the band was playing and by the music's intensity. 
We actually found those orbs downtown in N.Y.C at an art gallery and we put our hands up to them and the electricity would follow our hands wherever they went.
Anyway,I digress-- let's get on with the show, let's go!
Solid Jack Straw-  they throw in a ONE MORE TIME during the lyrics. Me thinks that is a slight nod to the 20th anniversary. But I don't remember that added lyric anywhere else in 85. (I will have to keep listening)
Anyway, Dupree's is hot, they seemed to play it pretty regularly in 85.
Minglewood-So hot live and the ladies dug it as well.
Listen to Garcia getting going for B.E. Women.
 I never  could hear this live without crying tears of joy. Such a sweet tune. Garcia could struggle with this one at times lyrically but when he put the metal to the pedal it was pure bliss.
"Lilah Jones went to meet her God..."
----Hey Bobby how bout a rock and roll song?
ESAU- one of the treats of 1985.
Great story song with plenty of twists and turns. 
All kinds of discussions about the lyrics on this tune.
Altamont, Vietnam, Old Testament, The Apocalypse
 I just dig the way this tune has its own distinct sound. 
"I dreamed one night, we were holding hands,,
Shadowboxing the Apocalypse and wandering/watering
the land"
Bird Song-  this tune kept getting more jammy as the years went on. Now nothing is ever going to top the early years where Bird Song is so psychedelic it literally is a mini TRIP. but they jammed heavy on this tune in the 80s and 90s! No exception here as they start exploring the cosmos..
Brent-is bopping along.
Bucket-This song was good before it got the MTV treatment. After MTV if cell phones had been around people would have been taking selfies of "Me at a Dead show as the Grateful Dead play that HELL IN A BUCKET song from MTV"
Anyway, can't blame the song. It has a good riff, fun to dance and as my buddy gave me this warning, "it is about vengeance, man" Anyway if you have heard any of Joan Baez folky tunes this song should make you at least chuckle. And besides this is the video gave the AFLAC duck his start.
"Hey Sally, Ride, Ride, Ride"
Mighty Swell--Might as Well--You weren't dancing for this, you were already passed out.
Some Laryngitis for the JER man- went with the territory in 1985. He just sings right thru it.
Set 2
Truckin' -Always like this tune opening a set. Some Chula Vista cruiser during the opening lyrics. This is Not an oversized version but they tear it up. "Ain't it a shame"
Dig Brent singing "Sometimes the lights all shining on me"
Important thing is they jam out of 'truckin' not just shut it down. And really a nice segue into TERRAPIN. Whatever Garcia is lacking on his vocals he is more than sharp on the guitar.
Inspiration, due me rightly?
Not a huge fan of Women are Smarter. i think it has more to do with the placement of the tune. Plus Aiko is always much preferred in my book but since they are interwoven in that New Orleans sound the basic dance beat is the same. Hey we get some AIKO thrown in with a CHINESE NEW YEAR --Gung Hey Fat Chow! Pretty short pre-drums and not much going on after drums with Space>Throwing>Touch E) Johnny B 
HMMN-Solid 4 for set one
Not quite a 4 for set two (is that diplomatic enough)
Maybe they had plans for after the gig?
A reluctant 3
um I was there. I thought maybe we'd seen the on-stage break-up of the Grateful Dead. But yeah then there were many good years to come. It really was that bad tho...
